        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-3-vowels-part-2-and">Lesson #3: Vowels Part 2; इ i and ई ee</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Last lesson, <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/727352299/lesson-2-vowels-part-1-a-and-aa">Lesson #2; Vowels Part 1</a>, we started learning about the Vowels in Hindi. We learnt our first two vowels, can you remember them?,&nbsp;<big><big>&#2309;&nbsp;</big></big><em>a</em> and <big><big>&#2310;&nbsp;</big></big><em>aa. </em>We also learnt a few words that use these letters. Today we&rsquo;re going to continue with the vowel and learn the next two. So let&rsquo;s get straight into it!&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lz1d2kWc3m1qbzksh.png">&nbsp;<em>i &nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F19591788&amp;%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p><small><small>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; If you can&rsquo;t see the play button or if it wont work then <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/17326025481/problems-with-the-audio-files">click here</a> for instructions on how to fix it!</small></small></p><p>As usual click the play button above to hear the letter pronounced, be sure to keep listening to it!&nbsp;This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em>. What does it look like? Well it&rsquo;s a bit like a capital S with a line on top and a strange little tail.&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> is pronounced just like the i in the English word pit or hit. Make sure you listen to it many times! Again, like <big><big>&#2309;&nbsp;</big></big><em>a,&nbsp;</em><big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i&nbsp;</em>should make quite a short sound. Practice writing and saying the letter, <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em>, <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em>, <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em>. Got it? <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>acchaa </em>good!</p><p>Ready to learn a word that starts with <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em>?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/1130f92bb1ba38fddf97ab51a1c448e8/tumblr_inline_mndh9l2Jv91qz4rgp.png"></p><blockquote><div><p>Pretend for me that there&rsquo;s 21 candles on this cake because you&rsquo;re celebrating your 21st birthday!&nbsp;</p></div></blockquote><p><big><big>&#2311;&#2325;&#2381;&#2325;&#2368;&#2360;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ikkees </em>is the number Twenty One in Hindi. Can you see the letter <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> in the word? Yeah, that&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s right at the start. You can learn all the numbers in Hindi in the <a href="../../numbers">Numbers section</a>!&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F19591883&amp;%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>Click the play button above to hear the two example words with this letter pronounced; <big><big>&#2311;&#2325;&#2381;&#2325;&#2368;&#2360;</big></big> <em>ikkees</em>- Twenty One and <big><big>&#2330;&#2367;&#2337;&#2364;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366; </big></big> <em>ciriyaa</em> - Bird</p><p>When you want to add the vowel <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> to a consonant we use the symbol <big><big><big>&#2367;</big></big></big>. This can be quite confusing because it goes on the left hand side of the consonant, even though you make the vowel sound after.&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lav94cJAXl1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p>The Hindi word for bird is <big><big>&#2330;&#2367;&#2337;&#2364;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ciriyaa - </em>Can you see the letter <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> here? Have a look for the <big><big>&#2367;&nbsp;</big></big>symbol. Can you see it? Yeah, thats right, there&rsquo;s two! We have an <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> on <big><big>&#2330;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ca</em> giving <big><big>&#2330;&#2367;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ci</em>&nbsp;(pronounced like the start of &lsquo;chick&rsquo;) and we also have a <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> on <big><big>&#2337;&#2364;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ra</em> giving<big><big> &#2337;&#2364;&#2367;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ri</em>! Don&rsquo;t worry too much if this is confusing, all it takes is practice, promise.&nbsp;</p><p>Ready for the fourth vowel of Hindi? Here it is;&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lz1d7rioUz1qbzksh.png">&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>ee &nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F19591962&amp;%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter&nbsp;<big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee</em>.&nbsp;What does it look like? It&rsquo;s very similar to <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> but it has this flick on top, can you see the difference? <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> and <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee. </em>Got it?&nbsp;. <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee&nbsp;</em>is pronounced just like the 'ee&rsquo; in the words feet or see. It&rsquo;s a long vowel sound. eeeeeee. Ready to learn some words using <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee</em>?</p><p>When we want to add <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee</em> to a consonant we use this symbol; <big><big><big>&#2368;</big></big></big>. Let&rsquo;s see an example;&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lz1db2VVGp1qbzksh.png"></p><p>The word <big><big>&#2348;&#2367;&#2354;&#2381;&#2354;&#2368;</big></big> <em>billee</em>&nbsp;means cat in Hindi. Can you see the <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee&nbsp;</em> here? Yeah that&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s at the end; we have <big><big>&#2354;&#2368;</big></big> <em>lee. </em>Can you also see the letter <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> in this word? Yep, it&rsquo;s at the start, on the <big><big>&#2348;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ba</em> giving <big><big>&#2348;&#2367;&nbsp;</big></big><em>bi</em>.</p><p class="center"><iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F19592106&amp;%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe>&nbsp;</p><p>Click the play button above to here the two sample words of the letter pronounced; <big><big>&#2348;&#2367;&#2354;&#2381;&#2354;&#2368;</big></big> <em>billee</em> - Cat and <big><big>&#2360;&#2366;&#2337;&#2364;&#2368;</big></big> <em>saaree</em> - Sari.&nbsp;</p><p>It&rsquo;s really important to understand the differences in the symbols for these two vowels; the short vowel&nbsp;<big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> comes before the letter giving, for example,&nbsp;<big><big>&#2344;&#2367;</big></big> <em>ni</em> and the long vowel&nbsp;<big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee</em> comes after, giving <big><big>&#2344;&#2368;</big></big> <em>nee. </em>Can you see the difference? Don&rsquo;t worry if it takes sometime getting used to.&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/96287d58e1462308262849dbb5b712f3/tumblr_inline_mndhqtZXd51qz4rgp.jpg"><br>Image by <a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FFile%3AWomen_in_Sari.jpg&amp;t=M2NjM2I5ZjU3OTk1MjQ4MGY0NzkzYWVkNGFiZjUzMDhmYmYwMDZhNSxqc2RKRm9lOQ%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F732878148%2Flesson-3-vowels-part-2-%E0%A4%87-i-and-%E0%A4%88-ee&amp;m=0">wikipedia</a>.</p><p>Do you know what the women in the picture above are wearing? It&rsquo;s an Indian dress called a <big><big>&#2360;&#2366;&#2337;&#2364;&#2368; </big></big> <em> saaree</em> - mostly spelt Sari in English. Can you see the letter <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee</em> in this word? Yep, that&rsquo;s right it&rsquo;s at the end again!</p><p>So we&rsquo;ve learnt two more vowels today, <big><big>&#2311;&nbsp;</big></big><em>i</em> and <big><big>&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>ee. </em>Keep practicing them!&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../../vowels">Click here to go back to the Vowels Section</a>.</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/devanagari">devanagari</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/vowels">vowels</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/i">i</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/ee">ee</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/alphabet">alphabet</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/june2010">june2010</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="732878148" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_732878148"><iframe id="like_iframe_732878148" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=732878148&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=jsdJFoe9" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_732878148"></iframe></div><a href="https